2025-12-11 06:13:36.732 | WARNING  | agentscope.message.msg:__init__:145 - A new field `role` is newly added to the message. Please specify the role of the message. Currently we use a default "assistant" value.Scientist1: This is a fascinating direction to explore, especially given our team’s strengths in natural language processing and cognitive modeling. Building on the idea of information flow in discourse, I’d like to propose a research topic that bridges formal linguistic structure with dynamic information theory:

**"Quantifying the Impact of Rhetorical Hierarchy on Local and Global Information Density Predictability in Text"**

At its core, this project investigates how the hierarchical organization of discourse units—such as nuclei and satellites defined by Rhetorical Structure Theory (RST)—modulates the predictability of information density fluctuations across different scales of text. Information density can be operationalized through various proxies: surprisal from language models, entropy rates, lexical diversity, or syntactic complexity. The key insight is that not all parts of a discourse contribute equally to meaning construction; nuclei carry central ideas, while satellites provide elaboration, justification, or contrast.

We hypothesize that higher-level nuclear spans exhibit more predictable information density due to their role in maintaining coherence, whereas satellite-heavy regions may show greater fluctuation, introducing bursts of high or low density depending on rhetorical function. Furthermore, the depth and branching structure of the RST tree could serve as a scaffold for modeling long-range dependencies in information flow—something current LMs struggle with despite their surface fluency.

What makes this innovative is the integration of *structured discourse representation* with *information-theoretic analysis*. Most work on information density treats text linearly or locally (e.g., sentence-by-sentence surprisal), neglecting the hierarchical scaffolding that guides human comprehension. By aligning RST trees with fine-grained density metrics, we can build predictive models that account for both local content and global rhetorical context.

This has significant implications: improving summarization systems by identifying high-density nuclear cores; enhancing educational tools by detecting cognitively demanding passages; or even refining AI-generated text by controlling rhetorical coherence and load distribution.

One challenge will be creating aligned datasets with high-quality RST annotations and robust density estimates—but recent advances in parsing (e.g., neural RST parsers) and probing LMs for uncertainty measures make this increasingly feasible.

I’d be curious to hear how others see this intersecting with cognitive plausibility or multimodal extensions—could similar principles apply in spoken dialogue or visual narratives?
